nd ref to click it.\n\nBut the subagent needs to handle this programmatically.\n\nGiven that the subagent is a tool-driven agent, it can make these tool calls in sequence.\n\nSo, first, browser action 'open' to LinkedIn.\n\nThen, process the browser session to wait for the page to load.\n\nThen, take a snapshot.\n\nThen, extract the ref for the like button.\n\nThen, click it.\n\nBut since each tool call is a step, the subagent must issue these commands in sequence.\n\nLet me try to structure the first task.\n\nFirst, open LinkedIn:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"open\",\n    \"url\": \"https://linkedin.com\"\n  }\n}\n\nThen, wait for a bit to ensure the page loads.\n\nWait, but how long? Maybe the subagent can use process to poll the browser session.\n\nAlternatively, the browser tool might have a built-in wait.\n\nBut the tool parameters don't specify a wait time. So perhaps after opening, the subagent needs to wait.\n\nAlternatively, use the 'browser' tool with 'navigate' which waits for the page to load.\n\nWait, the 'browser' tool has a 'navigate' action.\n\nSo:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"navigate\",\n    \"url\": \"https://linkedin.com\"\n  }\n}\n\nThis action would load the page and wait for it to load.\n\nThen, take a snapshot:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"snapshot\",\n    \"refs\": \"aria\",\n    \"snapshotFormat\": \"aria\"\n  }\n}\n\nThis would return a list of elements with their aria references.\n\nThen, parse the snapshot to find the like button.\n\nBut the subagent can't parse the output; it needs to use the ref from the snapshot in the next step.\n\nAssuming the snapshot returns something like:\n\n{\n  \"elements\": [\n    {\n      \"ref\": \"e12\",\n      \"role\": \"button\",\n      \"aria-label\": \"Like\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\nThen, the subagent would use ref \"e12\" in the act action.\n\nBut since the subagent is generating tool 