ubagent must follow the sequence: like_post, send_connection_request, etc.\n\nSo, task 1:\n\n- Open LinkedIn (if not open)\n- Click Like button on a post.\n\nBut how to know when the browser is open? The subagent needs to handle the browser session.\n\nAssuming the subagent starts with a fresh browser session.\n\nSo:\n\nCall browser open to LinkedIn.\n\nThen, wait for the page to load (maybe the navigate action handles this).\n\nThen, click the like button.\n\nSo, tool calls:\n\n1. browser open LinkedIn URL\n2. browser act click the like button\n\nBut to be precise:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"open\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.linkedin.com\"\n  }\n}\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"act\",\n    \"kind\": \"click\",\n    \"selector\": \"[aria-label=\\\"Like\\\"]\"\n  }\n}\n\nThen, move to task 2: send_connection_request\n\nFor sending a connection request, the subagent needs to:\n\n- Find a profile to connect with.\n- Click the \"Connect\" button.\n\nAssuming the profile is visible on the feed.\n\nSo, steps:\n\n1. Open the profile page.\n2. Click \"Connect\" button.\n\nBut this is more complex. Maybe the subagent needs to find a specific person.\n\nAlternatively, the task might involve sending a connection request to a specific person, but the context doesn't specify.\n\nGiven that the user provided \"send_connection_request\" as a task, the subagent needs to perform this action.\n\nAgain, using the browser tool:\n\n- Navigate to a target person's profile.\n- Click the \"Connect\" button.\n\nAssuming the target is a person visible on the feed.\n\nSo, first, find a person's profile link.\n\nTake a snapshot to get element references.\n\nThen, click on the profile link.\n\nThen, on the profile page, click \"Connect\".\n\nBut this is more involved.\n\nHowever, the subagent needs to follow the sequence, so it has to proceed step by step.\n\nBut given the complexity, the subagent must proceed with the available tools.\n\nGiven time constraints, the subagent should proceed with the browser tool calls for each task.\n\nNow, considering that each task is a separate action, the subagent needs to perform all six tasks.\n\nThe main challenge is that each task requires navigating to the correct page and interacting with specific elements.\n\nThe subagent must ensure each task is completed in sequence.\n\nAfter completing all tasks, the subagent must trigger the success callback.\n\nBut the user's instructions say that the success callback is to run a curl command when all tasks are done.\n\nSo, after completing task 6, the subagent should run the curl command.\n\nThe same for failure.\n\nNow, the subagent must execute each task in order.\n\nLet's outline the steps:\n\n1. like_post:\n   - Open LinkedIn (if not open)\n   - Click the Like button on a post\n\n2. send_connection_request:\n   - Navigate to a profile\n   - Click Connect\n\n3. post_comment:\n   - Find a post\n   - Click Comment\n   - Type the comment\n   - Submit\n\n4. page_follow_request:\n   - Find a company page\n   - Click Follow\n\n5. like_post:\n   - Like another post\n\n6. send_follow_up_message:\n   - Send a message to a connection\n\nEach of these steps requires browser interactions.\n\nBut given that the subagent is a generic worker, it needs to handle these steps via the browser tool.\n\nHowever, without specific context on the target posts, profiles, or companies, the subagent must make assumptions or rely on the current state of the browser.\n\nAssuming the browser is open and logged in, the subagent can proceed.\n\nNow, the main problem is that the subagent's tool calls must be precise.\n\nFor example, the first task:\n\nTool call to open LinkedIn:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"open\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.linkedin.com\"\n  }\n}\n\nThen, to click Like button:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"browser\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"action\": \"act\",\n    \"k